data(iris)
iris

Scatterplot

Version 1: Simple Scatterplot

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Petal.Length, y = Petal.Width)) +
  geom_point()

Version 2: with added dimension, color and shape for species.

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Petal.Length, 
                 y = Petal.Width,
                 shape = Species,
                 color = Species)) +
  geom_point()

Version 3: with a fitted line

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Petal.Length, 
                 y = Petal.Width)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = Species,
                 shape = Species)) +
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Version 4: With fitted (straight) line and removing the confidence band

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Petal.Length, 
                 y = Petal.Width)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = Species,
                 shape = Species)) +
  geom_smooth(color = "black", method = "lm", se = F)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Petal.Length, 
                 y = Petal.Width)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = Species,
                 shape = Species)) +
    geom_smooth(color = "black", method = "lm", se = F)+
    theme_bw()+ 
    theme(plot.title = 
              element_text(hjust = 0.5))+
    ggtitle(label = "Petal width and length of different flower species")+
    xlab("Length of Petal")+
    ylab("Width of Petal")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Exercise

The mpg file comes with the ggplot2 package. It contains data about fuel economy of different cars.

mpg
  • displ engine displacement, in liters
  • hwy highway miles per gallon
  • drv the type of drive train, where f = front-wheel drive, r = rear wheel drive, 4 = 4wd

Create a scatterplot with the displacement on the x axis, highway miles per gallon on the y axis, and the type of drive train as the color legend.

## answer here
ggplot(mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy))+
    geom_point(aes(color = drv))+
    geom_smooth(method = "lm",
                se = F)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Line Charts

Recall, line charts are commonly used to visualize trend over time. Therefore, it is important that know how to manipulate dates suitable for a ggplot line chart. Suppose the airquality data which contains air quality measurements in New York in 1973.

airquality

We add a Date column. The function make_date is in the lubridate package. If we have a proper Date column, manipulation and visualization will be more intuitive.

library(lubridate)
## 
## Attaching package: 'lubridate'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     date, intersect, setdiff, union
airquality %>%
  mutate(Date = make_date(year = 1973, 
                          month = Month, 
                          day = Day)
         )%>% select(c(Temp, Date))
airquality %>%
  mutate(Date = make_date(year = 1973, 
                          month = Month, 
                          day = Day)
         ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Date, y = Temp)) +
  geom_line()

airquality %>%
  mutate(Date = make_date(year = 1973, 
                          month = Month, 
                          day = Day)
         ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Date, y = Temp)) +
  geom_line()+
    scale_x_date(date_breaks = "2 months", date_labels = "%d-%b-%y")

Exercise

The Orangedataset contains measurements of the growth of orange trees over time.

Orange

The Tree column is an ordered factor, but the order is not intuitive. We reorder the levels using the following chunk.

Orange$Tree <- ordered(Orange$Tree, levels = c(5,4,3,2,1))
levels(Orange$Tree)
## [1] "5" "4" "3" "2" "1"

Now, create a line chart with age on the x axis, circumference on the y axis, and the Tree group as color legend.

## type your answer here!
ggplot(Orange, aes(x = age, y = circumference))+
    geom_line(aes(color = Tree))

Histogram and Density Plots

Initializing a dataset.

set.seed(125)
norm1 <- rnorm(100, mean = 1, sd = 3)
norm2 <- rnorm(100, mean = 8, sd = 2)
norm3 <- rnorm(100, mean = 15, sd = 3)
norm.dat <- data.frame(norm1, norm2, norm3) %>% 
    pivot_longer(cols = c("norm1", "norm2", "norm3"))
## Type in this chunk when following the codes on the screen
ggplot(norm.dat, aes(x = value))+
    geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

# final code
ggplot(norm.dat, aes(x = value))+
    geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), bins = 10)+
    stat_function(fun = dnorm, 
                  args = list(
                      mean = mean(norm.dat$value),
                      sd = sd(norm.dat$value)))

ggplot(norm.dat, aes(x = value, 
                     fill = name))+
    geom_histogram(bins = 10, 
                   position = "identity",
                   alpha = 0.5,
                   color = "white",
                   aes(y = ..density..))

Boxplots

ggplot(norm.dat, aes(x = value, fill = name))+
    geom_boxplot()+
    scale_fill_viridis_d()+
    theme(axis.text.y=element_blank())

ggplot(norm.dat, aes(y = value, fill = name))+
    geom_boxplot()+
    scale_fill_viridis_d()+
    theme(axis.text.x=element_blank())

Bar Chart and Variations

For this part, let’s use the satisfaction data

satisfaction <- read_csv("employee satisfaction.csv")
## Rows: 2500 Columns: 10
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (8): emp_id, birthdate, sex, daily_rate, department, work_life, relation...
## dbl (2): age, work_tenure
## 
## ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
## ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
satisfaction

Version 1: 1 chart, same y axis for all.

ggplot(satisfaction, 
       aes(x = department)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill = work_life),
           stat = "count",
           position = "dodge")

Version 2: Different charts, different y axes.

ggplot(satisfaction, 
       aes(x = department)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill = work_life),
           stat = "count",
           position = "dodge") +
  facet_wrap(. ~ department, scale = "free")

Version 3: Stacked bar chart

ggplot(satisfaction, 
       aes(x = department)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill = work_life),
           stat = "count",
           position = "stack")

Version 4: 100% stacked bar chart. Set position = "fill"

ggplot(satisfaction, 
       aes(x = department)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill = work_life),
           stat = "count",
           position = "fill")

Version 5: flipped coordinates

ggplot(satisfaction, 
       aes(x = department)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill = work_life),
           stat = "count",
           position = "fill") +
  coord_flip()
